<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-11-25T20:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-11-25T20:00:00-05:00" n="761" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d761">
                    <note rend="inline" type="source">611.9331/11–2644: Telegram</note>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Atcheson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                        </hi>
                    </head>
                    <opener>
                        <dateline rendition="#right">
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-11-26T08:00:00+07:00">November 26,
                                1944—8 a.m.</date>
                            <lb/> [Received 2 p.m.]</dateline>
                    </opener>
                    <p>1908. Director of Foreign Office Treaty Department informs me that Chinese
                        draft of commercial treaty is almost ready for presentation. We shall, I
                        feel, have lost the considerable advantages to accrue from putting the
                        Chinese Government on notice as to our desires and expectations, as well as
                        some bargaining advantages, if their draft is presented before ours.</p>
                    <closer>
                        <signed>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Atcheson</hi>
                        </signed>
                    </closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>